Welcome! For this session were going to work with the stringr package (make sure you have installed it!) and regex. This package is designed to manipulate strings, recall that you can create them with either single quotes or double quotes.

Check stringr documentation: https://stringr.tidyverse.org/articles/from-base.html#order-strings-1

string1 <- "This is a string"
string2 <- 'If you want to include a "quote" inside a string, please use single quotes'

String manipulation basics

We will work with a simple list of dog breeds 

dogs_data <- c("Border Collie","Akita","Labrador","Poodle","Miniature Schnauzer","Fox Terrier","Tibetan Mastiff")
  1. Which is the dog breed with the longest name in the list? Please calculate it and sum the string length in the entire list.
str_length(dogs_data)
## [1] 13  5  8  6 19 11 15
sum(str_length(dogs_data)) #If you need to know the lenght of the entire list, you can just use sum()
## [1] 77
  1. Are you sure that you got the right number? Hint: beware of whitespaces
str_length(str_replace_all(dogs_data," ",""))
## [1] 12  5  8  6 18 10 14
  1. Please indicate which breeds contain an a in its name.
str_subset(dogs_data, "a")
## [1] "Akita"               "Labrador"            "Miniature Schnauzer"
## [4] "Tibetan Mastiff"
  1. Did you realized that it only returns the breeds written in lowercase? Find a way to convert all breeds to lowercase and repeat the previous step.
str_subset(str_to_lower(dogs_data), 'a')
## [1] "akita"               "labrador"            "miniature schnauzer"
## [4] "tibetan mastiff"
  1. Look for the position of breeds with an uppercase I but make sure that it takes into account all breeds.
str_subset(str_to_upper(dogs_data), 'I')
## [1] "BORDER COLLIE"       "AKITA"               "MINIATURE SCHNAUZER"
## [4] "FOX TERRIER"         "TIBETAN MASTIFF"
  1. Count the number of t letters in the list.
str_count(dogs_data, "t")
## [1] 0 1 0 0 1 0 2
  1. Replace with an exclamation the first a in each breed. Hint: beware of lower and uppercases.
str_replace(str_to_lower(dogs_data), "a", "!")
## [1] "border collie"       "!kita"               "l!brador"           
## [4] "poodle"              "mini!ture schnauzer" "fox terrier"        
## [7] "tibet!n mastiff"
  1. Pick Miniature Schnauzers and retrieve the second part of the name using str_sub().
str_sub(str_subset(dogs_data, "schnauzer"), 11, 19)
## character(0)

Manipulating sentences

  1. You can also work with sentences and convert string to sentence. Use this sentence " schnauzers were Originally Bred to be ratters, guard Dogs, and All-purpose Dogs On German farms."
str_to_sentence("  schnauzers were Originally Bred to be ratters, guard Dogs,     and All-purpose Dogs On German farms.")
## [1] "  Schnauzers were originally bred to be ratters, guard dogs,     and all-purpose dogs on german farms."
  1. The sentence looks better, but we still have some white spaces in between it. Please trim it.
str_trim("  Schnauzers were originally bred to be ratters, guard dogs,     and all-purpose dogs on german farms.") 
## [1] "Schnauzers were originally bred to be ratters, guard dogs,     and all-purpose dogs on german farms."
  1. Some white spaces in between are still there, please remove them as well.
str_squish("  Schnauzers were originally bred to be ratters, guard dogs,     and all-purpose dogs on german farms.")
## [1] "Schnauzers were originally bred to be ratters, guard dogs, and all-purpose dogs on german farms."
  1. Now we actually want that white space back, but we only need it at the beginning and end of it.
str_pad("Schnauzers don't bite", width = 60, side="both") 
## [1] "                   Schnauzers don't bite                    "

Using RegEx

### The next list contains words with some pronunciations and typos. Our task is to standarize all the names and remove useless puntuations.

dogs_data <- c("Border Collie", "akita!", "LABRADOR", "Poodle.", "miniature schnauzer", "FOX TERRIER", 
"Tibetan Mastiff")
  1. Remove punctuations to standarize the list and save it as a new object called clean_list.
clean_list <- str_replace_all(dogs_data, "[:punct:]","")
  1. We want to rewrite all breeds in a nice format, use the previously saved object (clean_list), in which only the first letter is uppercased.
str_to_title(clean_list)
## [1] "Border Collie"       "Akita"               "Labrador"           
## [4] "Poodle"              "Miniature Schnauzer" "Fox Terrier"        
## [7] "Tibetan Mastiff"

We will now use a list that contains the same info the the previous one, but the count of number of dogs is preceded by an underscore.

dog_count_pattern <- c("Border Collie_23", "Akita_11", "Labrador_24", "Poodle_1", "Miniature Schnauzer_80", "Fox Terrier_3", "Tibetan Mastiff_6")
  1. Split the name and the quantity of dogs using str_split().
str_split(dog_count_pattern, "_")

str_split_fixed(dog_count_pattern, "_", 2)

str_detect(dog_count_pattern, " ")

str_detect(dog_count_pattern, "[:space:]") #using regex
